when roll out a deployment, it creates replicasets 
to deploy to a new version:
option 1:
in deployment-definition file, update the version number at spec.template.spec.containers.image
$ k apply -f deployment.definition.yml

option 2:
$ k set image deployment/myapp=deployment nginx=nginx:1.9.1


two different StrategyTyle:
Recreate    //shut down all the environments which have the old version, and deploy the new version to all the environments, it would have a short outrage
RollingUpdate    //default

there are more deployment strategy:
Blue/green: 100% tranffic is still rolled to the old version, at this point of time test is run on new version, once test passes, switch all the traffic to the new version at once
implementation: 
we create a service to route traffic to the old version by setting a label on the pods, we use the same label as a selector on the service; on the new deployment pod, once test passes,
we route all the traffic from the service to the new pod by switching the label selector on the service, just specify the selector in the service to the new pod. 

Canary: create a canary pod, roll out a new version with a small trafic and test on the new pod, if test passes, roll out new version to all the existing replicasets, then kill the canary pod; 
important in production
implementation:
add a same label to both old version and new version deployment pods as well as the selector in the service file, then since service distribute traffic evenly to pods, say, 
if we have 4 replicas in old version, 1 replica in canary, the traffic would be distributed 80% to old version and 20% to canary.


status:
$ k rollout status deployment/myapp-deployment
$ k rollout history deployment/myapp-deployment

rollback a deployment:
$ k rollout undo deployment myapp-deployment
verify:
$ k get replicasets


steps of performing deployments:
create
rollout
verify: rollout history


